post_text:
WEEKLY CHALLENGE

This week our challenge is to celebrate Teacher Appreciation Week. I have five challenges! You can do one per day or in any way that fits your schedule. You may enter once per student per challenge.

Monday – Send an email to a teacher thanking them for what they do. Include Mr. Lewis in the email to be entered to win.

Tuesday – Share a favorite or funny memory of your teacher from this year and post it to the Elementary Facebook page. (I will create a post specifically for this)

Wednesday – Write a thank you note to a teacher on the north side of the playground. Chalk will be provided. Mr. Lewis will take pictures. If you cannot make it to the playground put it on your own sidewalk. (I will create a post for you to post your picture)

Thursday – Make a thank you card for your teacher and post a picture of you with the card on the Elementary Facebook page. (I will make a post for this)

Friday – Post a video to your own Facebook page thanking a teacher. Be sure to tag the Elementary page to enter to win.

post_text:
Weekly Challenge

Are you celebrating May Day? Friday, May 1, 2020 is almost here!

In the 19th and 20th centuries, people welcomed the first of May by gathering flowers from the end of April’s showers and arranged them with pretty paper and small gifts like candy. They hung them on the door of people they cared about, both friends and neighbors, to welcome the warm weather. Modern May Day celebrations include ringing the recipient’s doorbell and running away without getting caught or the recipient gives the giver a kiss!

How can you make your own May Day basket? You can use many things as your container! Plastic cups, paper bags, jars, whipped topping containers, cottage cheese containers, or even a green plastic strawberry container all work! Cover them with pretty paper and punch holes on each side. Run ribbon, twine, string, or pipe cleaners through each hole and make a handle. Fill your container with candy or flowers.

During this time of social distancing, make someone’s day by leaving a May Day basket on the step of people you know and even those you don’t know.
text:
Weekly Challenge

Are you celebrating May Day? Friday, May 1, 2020 is almost here!

In the 19th and 20th centuries, people welcomed the first of May by gathering flowers from the end of April’s showers and arranged them with pretty paper and small gifts like candy. They hung them on the door of people they cared about, both friends and neighbors, to welcome the warm weather. Modern May Day celebrations include ringing the recipient’s doorbell and running away without getting caught or the recipient gives the giver a kiss!

How can you make your own May Day basket? You can use many things as your container! Plastic cups, paper bags, jars, whipped topping containers, cottage cheese containers, or even a green plastic strawberry container all work! Cover them with pretty paper and punch holes on each side. Run ribbon, twine, string, or pipe cleaners through each hole and make a handle. Fill your container with candy or flowers.

During this time of social distancing, make someone’s day by leaving a May Day basket on the step of people you know and even those you don’t know.

We are very excited to announce our Community Activity for April 6th-April 12th! We will be having an alphabet scavenger hunt. Many families and businesses have agreed to make a letter to display in the window of their home or business for you to FIND! Get your immediate family (those that live in your house) together for a walk, bike ride, or car ride to go and seek all of the letters. Count how many of each you find. We encourage you to take pictures and have fun! Remember your social distancing etiquette as you hunt! Post pictures for your chance to win!!!

CLICK ON THE LINK NOT THE PREVIEWED DOC. I have updated the addresses but it did not change the document. Sorry for the inconvenience.

https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1O7hvKctQLavXFLJfjQH2FFy6wpC1eI_ey-AwEEVosuw/edit?ts=5e8d1390#gid=0

I did a read-aloud with the book Going on a Bear Hunt. I challenge our families to get out of the house and do a bear hunt of their own. You can take part by putting a bear in your window or by getting out with your family and finding bears. Many of you have already expressed interest in being part of the bear hunt. If you responded earlier and I had access to your address I put you on the list. If you want to be part of the bear hunt and your address is not on the attached document please email me at rob.lewis@k12.sd.us and I will add your address. I would like the bear hunt to go on from Monday to Monday to give families plenty of time to take part. While doing your bear hunt stop by one of our local businesses to grab a treat of your liking.

https://docs.google.com/document/d/1-qmEBW06ghoyD6DygusqG5TEqqK3SVwSygQVj35a_ss/edit?usp=sharing
